var tafsirData_33 = {
  1: {
    "O Prophet! ˹Always˺ be mindful of Allah": "This is a direct address from Allah to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), commanding him to maintain constant consciousness of Allah in all his affairs. Being mindful of Allah means to be aware of His presence, to obey His commands, and to avoid what He has forbidden. Even though the Prophet was already the most God-conscious of all people, this command serves to reinforce and encourage him, and also to teach all believers that no one is above the need for this reminder. It is like a coach telling the best player on the team to keep practicing—not because they are lacking, but to maintain excellence.",
    "and do not yield to the disbelievers and the hypocrites": "Allah instructs the Prophet not to compromise the truth or follow the suggestions of those who openly reject faith (disbelievers) or those who pretend to believe while hiding disbelief in their hearts (hypocrites). During the Prophet's time in Medina, both groups tried to influence him through various tactics—sometimes through false advice, sometimes through pressure. This verse establishes that divine guidance must always take precedence over human pressure, no matter how powerful or persuasive the source may be.",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah concludes this verse by affirming two of His perfect attributes. He is All-Knowing, meaning nothing escapes His knowledge—He knows the plots of the disbelievers, the hidden intentions of the hypocrites, and what is best for the believers. He is All-Wise, meaning every command He gives is based on perfect wisdom. This reassures the Prophet and all believers that following Allah's guidance is always the right choice because it comes from the One who knows everything and whose decisions are flawless."
  },
  2: {
    "Follow what is revealed to you from your Lord": "The Prophet is commanded to adhere strictly to the Quran and divine revelation as his guide in all matters. This means his decisions, judgments, and teachings must all be based on what Allah reveals, not on personal opinion or external pressure. This principle also applies to all Muslims after him—we are to follow the Quran and the authentic teachings of the Prophet. The Quran is our map, and we must not create our own paths when Allah has already shown us the way.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Aware of what you ˹all˺ do": "Allah sees and knows every action, whether public or private, significant or minor. The shift to addressing everyone (\"you all\") indicates that this awareness extends to the entire community, not just the Prophet. This serves as both a comfort and a warning: comfort because Allah sees our sincere efforts and struggles, and warning because He also sees any deviation or disobedience. Nothing is hidden from Him."
  },
  3: {
    "And put your trust in Allah": "After commanding mindfulness and obedience, Allah now instructs the Prophet to place complete reliance on Him. Trust in Allah means doing what is required while leaving the results to Him. It does not mean being passive or lazy; rather, it means working hard while believing that the outcome is in Allah's hands. The Prophet faced enormous challenges—enemies from outside and hypocrites from within—yet he was told to trust Allah completely. This teaches us that when we have done our part, we should not be consumed by worry but should rely on Allah.",
    "for Allah is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs": "Allah declares that He alone is enough to handle all matters. A trustee is someone who manages affairs on behalf of another. When Allah is your Trustee, you have the most powerful, wise, and caring manager of your life. This phrase brings immense comfort: no matter how overwhelming the situation, Allah is sufficient. The Prophet Ibrahim was thrown into fire and said, \"Allah is sufficient for me\" (Hasbunallah), and the fire became cool and safe. When believers trust Allah as their Trustee, they find peace even in storms."
  },
  4: {
    "Allah does not place two hearts in any person's chest": "This is a powerful statement establishing a fundamental truth: a person cannot have divided ultimate loyalties. Just as physically no one has two hearts, spiritually a person cannot truly serve two opposing masters. This was revealed partly in response to claims some Arabs made about having \"two hearts\" (exceptional intelligence), but more importantly, it sets the foundation for the rulings that follow. A person cannot claim their wife is like their mother while she remains their wife, nor can they claim an adopted child is their biological child. Truth is singular and clear.",
    "Nor does He regard your wives as ˹unlawful for you like˺ your real mothers, ˹even˺ if you say they are": "In pre-Islamic Arabia, a man could say to his wife \"You are to me like my mother's back\" (called Zihar), which was a cruel practice that left women in limbo—neither properly married nor divorced. The man would avoid his wife as if she were his mother (unlawful for intimacy) but would not release her to remarry. Allah declares that merely saying such words does not change reality. Your wife does not become your mother just because you say so. This practice was abolished, and specific rules were later given for expiation if someone made such a statement (see Surah Al-Mujadilah 58:2-4).",
    "Nor does He regard your adopted children as your real children": "This verse establishes a crucial distinction: adoption in Islam does not create the same legal relationship as biological parentage. In pre-Islamic Arabia, adopted children were considered exactly like biological children in all respects—they inherited, they observed the same marriage prohibitions, and they took the father's name. Allah clarifies that while caring for orphans is highly rewarded, calling them your own children does not make them so. This revelation came in the context of Zaid ibn Harithah, who was adopted by the Prophet and was known as \"Zaid ibn Muhammad\" until this verse was revealed.",
    "These are only your baseless assertions": "Allah describes these pre-Islamic customs as mere words without substance. Saying something does not make it true. A wife does not become a mother through a verbal formula, and an adopted child does not become a biological child through naming conventions. These were cultural practices that contradicted reality, and Allah corrects them.",
    "But Allah declares the truth, and He ˹alone˺ guides to the ˹Right˺ Way": "In contrast to baseless human claims, Allah speaks only truth. His rulings are based on reality, justice, and wisdom. He guides humanity to what is correct in all matters—family relationships, social customs, and legal rights. Following His guidance leads to the straight path, while following human innovations leads to confusion and injustice."
  },
  5: {
    "Let your adopted children keep their family names": "This is a direct command to preserve the lineage of adopted children by calling them by their biological fathers' names. After this verse was revealed, Zaid was no longer called \"Zaid ibn Muhammad\" but \"Zaid ibn Harithah\" (his biological father's name). This ruling serves multiple purposes: it preserves family lineage and identity, ensures proper inheritance rights, maintains correct marriage prohibitions (an adopted daughter could marry the adoptive father's biological son, unlike a biological daughter), and protects the rights of biological families.",
    "That is more just in the sight of Allah": "Allah declares that maintaining truthful lineage is an act of justice. Falsifying lineage—even with good intentions—leads to complications in inheritance, marriage, and family rights. Islam values truth and accuracy in all matters, especially those affecting legal rights. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever claims to belong to someone other than his father, knowing that he is not his father, Paradise will be forbidden to him\" (Bukhari and Muslim). This shows how seriously Islam takes the preservation of accurate lineage.",
    "But if you do not know their fathers, then they are ˹simply˺ your fellow believers and close associates": "For orphans or foundlings whose fathers are unknown, they should be referred to as brothers in faith or as close associates/friends. This maintains their dignity while being truthful. The terms \"brothers in faith\" and \"close associates\" (mawali) indicate a relationship of love, care, and protection without falsely claiming biological ties. This shows that Islam creates bonds of brotherhood that can be just as strong as—or stronger than—blood ties, while still maintaining truthfulness.",
    "There is no blame on you for what you do by mistake": "Allah, in His mercy, does not hold people accountable for unintentional errors. If someone accidentally calls an adopted child by the wrong name out of habit (especially in the transition period after this verse was revealed), or makes a slip of the tongue, there is no sin. This principle applies broadly in Islamic law: genuine mistakes are forgiven.",
    "but ˹only˺ for what you do intentionally": "However, deliberate violation of this command—intentionally falsifying lineage while knowing the ruling—is sinful. Islam distinguishes between accidental errors and deliberate disobedience. The heart's intention is what matters. If someone persistently and knowingly calls an adopted child by a false lineage, they are held accountable.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah concludes with these two beautiful names, offering comfort to those who may have made mistakes in the past. Those who participated in pre-Islamic adoption practices before this ruling are forgiven. Those who slip up accidentally are forgiven. Allah's forgiveness is vast, and His mercy encompasses those who turn to Him sincerely."
  },
  6: {
    "The Prophet has a stronger affinity to the believers than they do themselves": "This verse establishes the unique and supreme position of the Prophet (peace be upon him) in relation to the believers. He has more right over them than they have over themselves. This means his commands take precedence, his love should be prioritized, and his guidance should be followed even over one's own desires. The Prophet himself explained this by saying: \"None of you truly believes until I am more beloved to him than his own self\" (Bukhari). Just as a wise and loving father has authority over his children for their own good, the Prophet's authority stems from his perfect guidance and sincere concern for the believers' welfare in this life and the next.",
    "And his wives are their mothers": "The wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him) are given the honored title of \"Mothers of the Believers.\" This title carries important implications: they deserve the utmost respect, they are permanently forbidden in marriage to any other man (even after the Prophet's death), and believers should treat them with the reverence due to mothers. However, this is a spiritual and legal status—it does not mean they are literally biological mothers, so inheritance rules between them and the believers do not apply. This status was exclusive to them and shows the special honor Allah gave to the Prophet's household.",
    "As ordained by Allah, blood relatives are more entitled ˹to inheritance˺ than ˹other˺ believers and immigrants": "In the early days of Islam in Medina, the Prophet established a system of brotherhood between the Meccan emigrants (Muhajiroon) and the Medinan helpers (Ansar), and they would even inherit from each other. This verse abrogated that practice, establishing that blood relatives have priority in inheritance matters. The strong bonds of faith remain, but inheritance follows family lines as Allah has ordained.",
    "unless you ˹want to˺ show kindness to your ˹close˺ associates ˹through bequest˺": "While blood relatives have priority in inheritance, a person can still show kindness to friends, associates, or even non-relative Muslims through bequests (wasiyyah). Islamic law allows a person to bequeath up to one-third of their wealth to non-heirs, enabling them to support friends, charitable causes, or others who would not otherwise inherit. This balances family rights with the freedom to do good.",
    "This is decreed in the Record": "This ruling is written in the Preserved Tablet (Al-Lawh Al-Mahfuz)—Allah's eternal record of all decrees. This emphasizes that these are not arbitrary human decisions but divine laws that have always been part of Allah's plan. The permanence of this decree shows its importance and that it should be accepted and followed without question."
  },
  7: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We took a covenant from the prophets": "Allah reminds us of the solemn covenant He took from all His prophets. A covenant is a binding agreement, a sacred promise. Every prophet was entrusted with the mission of delivering Allah's message faithfully to their people. This was not a casual responsibility but a formal pledge taken in the divine presence.",
    "as well as from you ˹O Prophet˺": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is directly addressed and included in this covenant. Despite being mentioned after the general category of \"prophets,\" he is specifically named first among the examples, highlighting his importance and the continuation of the prophetic mission through him.",
    "and from Noah, Abraham, Moses, and Jesus, son of Mary": "These five prophets are specifically mentioned: Muhammad, Noah, Abraham, Moses, and Jesus. They are known as the \"Prophets of Strong Resolve\" (Ulul Azm) because they showed exceptional patience and determination in delivering their messages despite severe opposition. Noah preached for 950 years, Abraham was thrown into fire, Moses confronted Pharaoh, Jesus faced rejection and plots against his life, and Muhammad endured persecution in Mecca and threats in Medina. Together, they represent the continuous chain of divine guidance throughout human history.",
    "We did take a solemn covenant from ˹all of˺ them": "Allah emphasizes that this covenant was not ordinary—it was solemn, heavy, and binding. The word \"solemn\" (ghaleez) indicates the weight and seriousness of this promise. The prophets were fully committed to delivering the truth, no matter the cost. This covenant bound them to convey the message completely, without alteration, addition, or concealment."
  },
  8: {
    "so that He may question these men of truth about their ˹delivery of the˺ truth": "The purpose of this covenant is explained: on the Day of Judgment, Allah will question the prophets about their mission. Did they deliver the message faithfully? Did they convey everything they were commanded to convey? This is not because Allah doesn't know—He knows everything—but to establish evidence and testimony before the people who received those messages. The prophets will testify that they delivered the truth, and then the people will be held accountable for how they responded. This shows the gravity of the prophetic mission and the accountability that comes with receiving divine guidance.",
    "And He has prepared a painful punishment for the disbelievers": "While the prophets will be honored for their faithfulness, those who rejected their message will face severe consequences. Allah has already prepared painful punishment for the disbelievers. The use of past tense (\"has prepared\") indicates certainty—this punishment is as good as already existing, waiting for those who reject the truth. This serves as a warning: the message has been delivered through the most trustworthy messengers, so there is no excuse for disbelief."
  },
  9: {
    "O believers! Remember Allah's favour upon you": "Allah addresses the believers directly, commanding them to remember and reflect upon His blessings. Remembering favors creates gratitude, strengthens faith, and provides comfort during future difficulties. The believers are asked to recall how Allah saved them when all seemed lost.",
    "when ˹enemy˺ forces came to ˹besiege˺ you ˹in Medina˺": "This refers to the Battle of the Trench (Ghazwat al-Khandaq) in the 5th year after Hijrah (627 CE). A confederation of enemies—the Quraysh of Mecca, the Ghatafan tribe, and other Arab tribes, along with the treacherous Jewish tribe of Banu Qurayza who broke their treaty—gathered an army of approximately 10,000 soldiers to destroy the Muslim community in Medina. The Muslims, numbering only about 3,000, were vastly outnumbered. On the advice of Salman al-Farsi, they dug a trench around the vulnerable parts of Medina, a defensive strategy unfamiliar to the Arabs.",
    "so We sent against them a ˹bitter˺ wind": "Allah intervened directly by sending a fierce, cold wind against the enemy forces. This wind was so severe that it overturned their tents, extinguished their fires, scattered their cooking pots, and made their stay unbearable. The timing and intensity of this wind was clearly miraculous—it affected the enemy camp severely while the Muslims were protected.",
    "and forces you could not see": "In addition to the wind, Allah sent unseen forces—angels—against the enemy. These invisible soldiers struck terror into the hearts of the confederates, caused confusion and discord among them, and demoralized them completely. The combination of the physical wind and the spiritual/angelic intervention shows that Allah fights for the believers in ways both seen and unseen.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of what you do": "Allah was watching everything throughout this crisis—the efforts of the believers in digging the trench, their steadfastness despite fear, and also the behavior of the hypocrites. This statement assures the believers that their efforts and sacrifices were witnessed by Allah and will be rewarded, while also warning that Allah saw those who showed weakness or treachery."
  },
  10: {
    "˹Remember˺ when they came at you from east and west": "The enemy forces approached from multiple directions—from the eastern highlands and from the western lowlands of Medina. This multi-directional siege created a feeling of being completely surrounded with no escape route. The phrase paints a picture of overwhelming military pressure from all sides.",
    "when your eyes grew wild ˹in horror˺": "The believers' eyes were shifting frantically due to fear and anxiety, looking in every direction at the approaching enemy, unable to focus. This is a natural human reaction to extreme danger. Allah describes this honestly, showing that the believers were genuinely terrified—they were not superhuman, but ordinary people facing an extraordinary threat.",
    "and your hearts jumped into your throats": "This vivid expression describes the intensity of the fear. When someone is extremely frightened, they feel their heart pounding so hard it seems to rise to their throat. The believers felt this level of terror as they saw the massive army surrounding their city. This description validates their fear while also setting up the contrast with their eventual steadfastness.",
    "and you entertained ˹conflicting˺ thoughts about Allah": "In this moment of crisis, different people had different thoughts. Some wavered, wondering if Allah's promise would really come true. Others remained firm in their trust. The hypocrites had negative thoughts, doubting Allah's support. This phrase captures the psychological warfare that extreme circumstances create, testing what people truly believe in their hearts. It distinguishes between those whose faith remained strong and those whose faith was shallow."
  },
  11: {
    "Then and there the believers were put to the test": "Allah explicitly states the purpose of this trial: it was a test of faith. Tests reveal the reality of a person's belief. When everything is easy, almost everyone claims faith. But when difficulty comes, true believers are distinguished from hypocrites. This test at the Battle of the Trench was one of the most severe the early Muslim community faced.",
    "and were violently shaken": "The believers experienced a severe shaking—emotionally, psychologically, and spiritually. The word used (zilzal) is the same root used for earthquakes, indicating how deeply this crisis affected them. Their certainties were tested, their patience was pushed to limits, and their trust in Allah was challenged. Yet those who passed this test emerged with stronger faith, while those who failed were exposed."
  },
  12: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when the hypocrites and those with sickness in their hearts said": "Allah now exposes what the hypocrites were saying during this crisis. Hypocrites are those who outwardly claim Islam but inwardly disbelieve. Those with \"sickness in their hearts\" refers to people with weak faith, doubt, or impure intentions. Both groups revealed their true nature under pressure. While believers draw closer to Allah during hardship, those with diseased hearts expose their inner corruption.",
    "\"Allah and His Messenger have promised us nothing but delusion!\"": "This was their statement of disbelief during the siege. They mockingly claimed that all the promises of victory, divine support, and ultimate triumph were lies and deception. They were referring to earlier prophecies that the Muslims would conquer the empires of Persia and Rome—which seemed absurd when they couldn't even defend their own city. They forgot that Allah's promises come true in His timing, not according to human impatience. Their mockery was recorded in the Quran, preserved forever as evidence of their hypocrisy and as a lesson for future generations."
  },
  13: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when a group of them said, \"O people of Yathrib!\"": "Some hypocrites called out to the Muslims using the old pre-Islamic name for Medina: \"Yathrib.\" The Prophet had renamed the city \"Madinah\" (the City) or \"Taybah\" (the Good), so using the old name showed disrespect for the Islamic identity of the city. This was a subtle form of undermining the new Muslim community's sense of identity and belonging.",
    "\"There is no point in you staying ˹here˺, so retreat!\"": "They spread defeatism and demoralization, telling people to abandon their defensive positions and flee. This was military sabotage—encouraging desertion during battle. Instead of strengthening resolve, they worked to break the community's will to resist. A true believer encourages patience and trust in Allah during difficulty; hypocrites spread despair and fear.",
    "Another group of them asked the Prophet's permission ˹to leave˺, saying, \"Our homes are vulnerable\"": "Some hypocrites tried a more subtle approach: they came to the Prophet with excuses, claiming their houses were unprotected and exposed to the enemy. They sought official permission to leave their posts under the guise of a legitimate concern.",
    "while ˹in fact˺ they were not vulnerable": "Allah exposes their lie: their homes were not actually unprotected. This was a false pretext. Allah knows the truth behind every excuse, and He reveals their deception in the Quran for all to see.",
    "They only wished to flee": "Their real intention is laid bare—they simply wanted to escape the danger. They were cowards who prioritized their own safety over the community's survival. Instead of being honest about their fear, they fabricated excuses. This teaches us that Allah knows our true intentions, and dishonesty about our motives is especially despicable."
  },
  14: {
    "Had their city been sacked from all sides": "Allah presents a hypothetical scenario: what if the enemy had actually broken through and invaded Medina from all directions?",
    "and they had been asked to abandon faith": "And what if the invaders demanded that these hypocrites renounce Islam and join them against the Muslims?",
    "they would have done so with little hesitation": "Allah reveals that these hypocrites would have quickly abandoned their supposed faith. Their Islam was only superficial—a convenience they would discard the moment it became dangerous. They would have betrayed the Muslim community with barely any resistance. This exposes the depth of their hypocrisy: their loyalty was never to Allah or His Messenger, only to their own survival and interests."
  },
  15: {
    "They had already pledged to Allah earlier never to turn their backs ˹in retreat˺": "Allah reminds us that these same hypocrites had previously made a formal promise to Allah that they would never flee from battle. After missing the Battle of Badr, some of them had sworn that if they got another chance, they would fight bravely and never run away. Now, when that chance came, they broke their promise and sought to flee.",
    "And a pledge to Allah must be answered for": "This is a severe warning: any promise made to Allah will be questioned on the Day of Judgment. Breaking such promises is not a small matter—it will be held against them. Allah does not forget pledges made in His name. This principle applies to all believers: every oath, promise, or commitment made invoking Allah's name carries weight and accountability."
  },
  16: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Fleeing will not benefit you if you ˹try to˺ escape a natural or violent death\"": "The Prophet is commanded to tell the hypocrites a fundamental truth: running away will not save them. Whether death comes naturally (from illness or old age) or violently (from battle or other causes), it is decreed by Allah. No one can escape their appointed time of death by fleeing. If Allah has decreed that someone will die at a certain time and place, no amount of running will change that. And if Allah has decreed that they will live, staying in battle will not kill them before their time.",
    "\"˹If it is not your time,˺ you will only be allowed enjoyment for a little while\"": "Even if they successfully flee and survive, what have they gained? Only a brief extension of worldly life. This life is temporary regardless—a few more years, then death comes anyway. By fleeing, they may preserve a short life but lose their honor, their relationship with Allah, and their place in the hereafter. The trade-off is terrible: eternal loss for temporary gain."
  },
  17: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Who can put you out of Allah's reach if He intends to harm you or show you mercy?\"": "This is a rhetorical question with an obvious answer: no one. If Allah decides to bring harm upon someone, there is no force in existence that can prevent it. And if Allah decides to show mercy to someone, no one can withhold that mercy. The hypocrites thought they could protect themselves by fleeing, but this question exposes the foolishness of that thinking. Protection and harm are both ultimately from Allah alone.",
    "They can never find any protector or helper besides Allah": "The conclusion is clear: there is no protector or helper other than Allah. The idols people worship, the powerful people they try to please, the safe places they try to hide—none of these can protect them from Allah's decree or save them if Allah withdraws His protection. True security comes only from being in Allah's favor, not from running away from difficulty."
  },
  18: {
    "Allah knows well those among you who discourage ˹others from fighting˺": "Allah is fully aware of who among the Muslim community was actively hindering the defense effort. These obstructors didn't just avoid fighting themselves—they worked to prevent others from fighting too. This is worse than personal cowardice; it's corruption that weakens the entire community.",
    "saying ˹secretly˺ to their brothers, \"Stay with us\"": "These hypocrites would quietly approach their friends and relatives, urging them to avoid the battle and join them in their homes. They spread their cowardice and defeatism through private conversations, trying to draw others into their disobedience. Their negative influence operated in whispers and shadows.",
    "and who themselves hardly take part in fighting": "And when they do occasionally join the believers, their participation is minimal and reluctant. They might show up to maintain appearances, but they contribute almost nothing. They're physically present but mentally and spiritually absent. This describes people who do the bare minimum while claiming credit, or who appear supportive in public while undermining efforts in private."
  },
  19: {
    "˹They are˺ totally unwilling to assist you": "These hypocrites are miserly with their support. They don't want to help with their wealth, their effort, or their presence. Everything about them is characterized by withholding and stinginess toward the believers.",
    "When danger comes, you see them staring at you with their eyes rolling like someone in the throes of death": "Allah paints a vivid picture of their behavior during danger. Their eyes roll around in terror, looking for escape routes, completely panicked. They look like someone about to die—pale, unfocused, paralyzed with fear. This is how the hypocrites behaved when the enemy was near: useless, terrified, looking at the Prophet and believers not for guidance but with the desperate eyes of someone awaiting death.",
    "But once the danger is over, they slash you with razor-sharp tongues, ravenous for ˹worldly˺ gains": "When the danger passes and victory comes, suddenly these same cowards become aggressive and demanding. They attack the believers with harsh criticism and sharp words, demanding their share of any spoils or gains. During the fight they were useless; after the fight they want the rewards. They are greedy for any worldly benefit while contributing nothing of value.",
    "Such people have not ˹truly˺ believed": "Allah delivers the verdict: these people are not believers, regardless of what they claim. Their actions reveal the truth. True faith is shown in consistent support, courage during trials, and contentment afterward. These hypocrites showed the opposite: cowardice during trials and greed afterward.",
    "so Allah has rendered their deeds void": "Because their \"faith\" was fake, any good deeds they may have done are nullified. Without sincere belief, actions have no value with Allah. It's like someone doing charity for show—the action happened, but the reward is lost because the intention was corrupt.",
    "And that is easy for Allah": "Nullifying their deeds is nothing difficult for Allah. He is not diminished by rejecting their empty actions, and they cannot argue or complain. What He decrees is done. This phrase also implies that dealing with hypocrites is a simple matter for Allah—they may think they are clever, but Allah easily exposes and handles them."
  },
  20: {
    "They ˹still˺ think that the enemy alliance has not ˹yet˺ withdrawn": "Even after Allah dispersed the enemy forces with the wind and unseen armies, the hypocrites couldn't believe the danger was over. Their fear was so deep that they remained paranoid, constantly expecting the enemy to return. This reveals their lack of trust in Allah's help and their underlying cowardice.",
    "And if the allies were to come ˹again˺, the hypocrites would wish to be away in the desert among nomadic Arabs, ˹only˺ asking for news about you ˹believers˺": "If another enemy force came, these hypocrites would wish they were far away in the desert, living among Bedouin tribes, safely removed from any danger. From that safe distance, they would merely inquire about what happened to the believers—not out of concern, but out of curiosity while protecting themselves. They would abandon the community entirely rather than stand with them.",
    "And if the hypocrites were in your midst, they would hardly take part in the fight": "Even if circumstances forced them to be physically present among the believers during battle, they would barely participate. Their hearts are not in it. They might hold weapons but wouldn't actually fight. They are a burden, not an asset—present in body but absent in spirit and courage."
  },
  21: {
    "Indeed, in the Messenger of Allah you have an excellent example": "This verse establishes a fundamental principle: Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is the best role model for humanity. His character, his actions, his responses to various situations—all of this is an example to be followed. During the Battle of the Trench, while hypocrites fled and complained, the Prophet was in the trench himself, carrying dirt, tying stones to his stomach out of hunger, and encouraging the believers. This is the example to follow. The Prophet once said, \"None of you truly believes until I am more beloved to him than his father, his child, and all of mankind\" (Bukhari). Following his example is an expression of that love.",
    "for whoever has hope in Allah and the Last Day": "The Prophet's example is especially meaningful for those who believe in Allah and are conscious of the Day of Judgment. Such people recognize that this life is temporary and that their actions have consequences. They want to meet Allah having lived well, and the best way to do that is to follow the Prophet's example. Someone who doesn't believe in the hereafter may not see the value, but for believers, the Prophet is the guide to Paradise.",
    "and remembers Allah often": "Those who follow the Prophet's example are also those who remember Allah frequently—in prayer, in supplication, in gratitude, and in every aspect of daily life. The Prophet himself was the greatest in remembrance of Allah, and his followers aspire to that same constant awareness of their Creator. Remembrance of Allah keeps the heart focused on what matters and provides strength during trials, just as it did during the Battle of the Trench."
  },
  22: {
    "When the believers saw the enemy alliance": "In contrast to the hypocrites who panicked and complained, the true believers responded differently when they saw the massive enemy force. Their reaction reveals the nature of genuine faith.",
    "they said, \"This is what Allah and His Messenger had promised us\"": "Instead of seeing the trial as a sign of Allah's abandonment, they recognized it as a fulfillment of prophecy. Allah had told them they would be tested (see Quran 2:214: \"Do you think you will enter Paradise without being tested?\"). The Prophet had told them that hardship precedes victory. When they saw the enemy, they said: \"This is exactly what we were told would happen.\" This perspective transforms trials from disasters into confirmations of truth.",
    "\"The promise of Allah and His Messenger has come true\"": "They affirmed the truthfulness of Allah and His Prophet. The trial itself was proof that they were on the right path, because the path of truth is always opposed by the forces of falsehood. When opposition comes, believers see it as confirmation, not refutation. The Prophet had promised that after hardship would come victory—they were simply in the hardship phase, with victory yet to come.",
    "And this only increased them in faith and submission": "Rather than weakening their faith, the trial strengthened it. They became more certain of Allah's promise and more submissive to His will. This is the sign of true faith: tests increase it rather than destroy it. Just as exercise strengthens muscles, trials strengthen genuine faith. The hypocrites' faith collapsed under pressure; the believers' faith grew."
  },
  23: {
    "Among the believers are men who have proven true to what they pledged to Allah": "Allah praises specific believers who kept their word. These were men who had promised Allah they would fight for His cause and sacrifice whatever was required. Unlike the hypocrites who broke their pledges at the first sign of danger, these men remained true to their word. One famous example is Anas ibn Nadr, who missed the Battle of Badr and swore to Allah that if he got another chance, Allah would see what he would do. At the Battle of Uhud, he fought until he was martyred with over 80 wounds on his body.",
    "Some of them have fulfilled their pledge ˹with their lives˺": "Some of these truthful men have already been martyred—they gave the ultimate sacrifice and fulfilled their promise completely. They died on the path of Allah, achieving the highest rank. The Prophet said, \"The martyrs are alive with their Lord, being provided for\" (Quran 3:169).",
    "others are waiting ˹their turn˺": "Other believers are still alive, waiting for their opportunity to fulfill their pledge. They haven't been martyred yet, but they are ready and willing. Their intention is pure, and they are simply waiting for Allah's decree—whether it's martyrdom or continued service in His cause.",
    "They have never changed ˹their commitment˺ in the least": "The key distinction between true believers and hypocrites is consistency. These believers never changed their commitment—not when times got hard, not when they saw the massive enemy army, not when their lives were in danger. Their word to Allah remained firm. This is the character of true faith: unwavering commitment regardless of circumstances."
  },
  24: {
    "˹It all happened˺ so Allah may reward the faithful for their faithfulness": "Allah explains the wisdom behind this trial: it was designed to distinguish the truthful from the liars, so that each group could receive what they deserve. The sincere believers who remained faithful will be rewarded for their truthfulness. Their patience, their courage, their trust in Allah—all of this will be recognized and rewarded. Tests serve to reveal character and provide grounds for reward.",
    "and punish the hypocrites if He wills": "As for the hypocrites, Allah may punish them for their treachery and lies. Their false claims of faith, their desertion during difficulty, their attempts to demoralize the community—all of this deserves punishment. The phrase \"if He wills\" shows that the matter is in Allah's hands.",
    "or turn to them ˹in mercy˺": "However, Allah leaves open the door of repentance even for hypocrites. If they sincerely repent, abandon their hypocrisy, and become truly faithful, Allah may forgive them. This shows Allah's immense mercy—even for those who have committed serious spiritual crimes, the path to forgiveness remains open. Many who showed weakness during the Battle of the Trench later became sincere believers.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "The verse concludes with these two beautiful names of Allah, emphasizing His willingness to forgive and His abundant mercy. For those who repent, there is hope. Allah's forgiveness is vast enough to cover even hypocrisy if one sincerely turns back to Him. This gives hope to anyone who has made mistakes—no sin is too great for Allah's mercy if one genuinely repents."
  },
  25: {
    "And Allah drove back the disbelievers in their rage, totally empty-handed": "After all their preparations, their massive army of 10,000 soldiers, their siege that lasted nearly a month, the disbelievers were forced to retreat in complete frustration. They left with nothing—no victory, no spoils, no achievement whatsoever. The bitter wind Allah sent, combined with the unseen forces and the internal discord He created among them, made their mission impossible. They had come with overwhelming confidence and left humiliated, their rage burning inside them because they couldn't accomplish anything. This is a powerful lesson: no matter how strong the enemies of truth appear, Allah can defeat them without the believers even having to fight directly.",
    "And Allah spared the believers from fighting": "This is one of the most remarkable aspects of this victory. Despite the massive enemy force, Allah protected the believers without requiring them to engage in full-scale battle. The trench prevented direct assault, and Allah's intervention dispersed the enemy before a major clash occurred. This demonstrates Allah's mercy and power—He can grant victory through means other than combat. The believers made their preparations, stood ready, and trusted Allah, and He took care of the rest.",
    "For Allah is All-Powerful, Almighty": "These two attributes explain how such a miraculous outcome was possible. Allah is All-Powerful (Qawiyy)—He possesses absolute strength and nothing can resist His will. He is Almighty (Aziz)—He is dominant and cannot be overcome. When these attributes are directed in favor of the believers, no enemy can stand. The confederates thought their numbers made them invincible, but against Allah's power, they were helpless."
  },
  26: {
    "And He brought down those from the People of the Book who supported the enemy alliance from their own strongholds": "This refers to the Jewish tribe of Banu Qurayza, who had a treaty with the Muslims but betrayed them during the siege by allying with the confederates. They lived in fortified settlements near Medina. After the confederates retreated, the Prophet (peace be upon him) immediately marched toward Banu Qurayza, as commanded by Jibreel. Despite their strong fortifications, Allah brought them down—they surrendered after a siege of about 25 days. Their treachery during the Muslims' most vulnerable moment was a grave violation that had to be addressed.",
    "and cast horror into their hearts": "Allah struck terror into the hearts of Banu Qurayza, making them unable to effectively resist despite their fortifications and preparations. This psychological defeat preceded the physical one. When Allah removes courage from hearts and replaces it with fear, no fortress can save its occupants. This is how Allah fights for the believers—through both physical and psychological means.",
    "You ˹believers˺ killed some, and took others captive": "After their surrender, Banu Qurayza requested to be judged by Sa'd ibn Mu'adh, a former ally of theirs. He judged them by their own scripture's law for treachery during wartime: the fighting men were executed, and the women and children were taken captive. This was not the Prophet's arbitrary decision but the judgment of someone they themselves chose, based on the laws they claimed to follow. The consequence was severe because the crime was severe—they had endangered the entire Muslim community at its most vulnerable moment."
  },
  27: {
    "He has also caused you to take over their lands, homes, and wealth": "Allah granted the Muslims the properties of Banu Qurayza—their agricultural lands, their houses, and their possessions. What had belonged to the treacherous was now given to those they had betrayed. This was a direct consequence of their violation of the treaty and their attempt to destroy the Muslim community. Allah provides for the believers from sources they never anticipated.",
    "as well as lands you have not yet set foot on": "This is a prophecy of future conquests. Allah promises the believers additional lands they had not yet reached—referring to the vast territories that would come under Muslim rule in the years and decades to come: the remaining parts of Arabia, Persia, Syria, Egypt, and beyond. At this moment, the Muslims had barely survived a siege, yet Allah was promising them future expansion. This built confidence and showed that the current victory was just the beginning.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything": "Whatever Allah promises, He is fully capable of fulfilling. The believers might have wondered how they could ever conquer distant lands when they had just struggled to defend their own city. But Allah is capable of everything. What seems impossible to human calculation is simple for Allah. This attribute should fill believers with hope and trust in Allah's promises, no matter how unlikely they seem."
  },
  28: {
    "O Prophet! Say to your wives": "Allah commands the Prophet to present a choice to his wives. This came at a time when some of his wives had requested more worldly provisions and comforts. The Prophet lived a simple life, often going without food for days, and his household shared this austere lifestyle. This verse addresses the tension between the demands of worldly comfort and the spiritual demands of being married to the Messenger of Allah.",
    "\"If you desire the life of this world and its luxury\"": "Allah presents the first option: if what the wives truly want is worldly comfort, wealth, luxury, and the pleasures of this temporary life, then they should be honest about that desire. There is no deception or pretense needed. This is a straightforward question about priorities and what one's heart truly seeks.",
    "\"then come, I will give you a ˹suitable˺ compensation ˹for divorce˺\"": "If they choose worldly life, the Prophet will provide them with appropriate financial compensation. They will not be left destitute or mistreated. Islam ensures that even in divorce, women are treated with dignity and given their rights.",
    "\"and let you go graciously\"": "The divorce would be conducted in the best manner, without bitterness, accusations, or humiliation. They would be released honorably to pursue the worldly life they desired. This shows the Islamic principle of parting with kindness when a relationship cannot continue. The Prophet would not force them to stay in a difficult situation, nor would he treat them badly for their choice."
  },
  29: {
    "\"But if you desire Allah and His Messenger and the ˹everlasting˺ Home of the Hereafter\"": "The second option is presented: if their hearts are truly attached to Allah, devoted to His Messenger, and focused on the eternal life to come rather than this temporary world, then they should remain. This choice requires prioritizing spiritual rewards over material comforts. It means accepting the simple lifestyle of the Prophet's household in exchange for something far greater.",
    "\"then Surely Allah has prepared a great reward for those of you who do good\"": "For those who choose this path and live it with excellence (ihsan), Allah promises an immense reward. The hardships and sacrifices of this world will be compensated many times over in the hereafter. All of the Prophet's wives chose this second option—they chose Allah, His Messenger, and the hereafter. Aisha (may Allah be pleased with her) reported that the Prophet started with her, and she immediately chose Allah and His Messenger. All the other wives made the same choice. This became a defining moment in their lives, cementing their status as the Mothers of the Believers."
  },
  30: {
    "O wives of the Prophet! If any of you were to commit a blatant misconduct": "Allah addresses the Prophet's wives directly, warning them about clear and obvious sins. Because of their elevated position as the Mothers of the Believers and their closeness to the Prophet, they are held to a higher standard. Their actions would have greater impact—both positive and negative—on the entire Muslim community. Leaders and those in prominent positions bear greater responsibility.",
    "the punishment would be doubled for her": "If any of them committed a clear sin, they would face twice the punishment that an ordinary woman would receive for the same offense. This is not because Allah is harsh, but because those who have more knowledge, more access to guidance, and higher status have greater accountability. A scholar who sins knows better than an ignorant person. A teacher who sets a bad example affects many students. The Prophet's wives were in the most privileged position imaginable, with direct access to revelation and the best example of humanity—so their accountability was proportionally greater.",
    "And that is easy for Allah": "Implementing this doubled punishment is simple for Allah. This phrase serves as a warning that Allah will not overlook such matters, and His ability to hold anyone accountable is absolute. It also implies that no one should think their status protects them from consequences."
  },
  31: {
    "And whoever of you devoutly obeys Allah and His Messenger and does good": "Just as punishment is doubled, so is reward. If any of the Prophet's wives shows devoted obedience to Allah and His Messenger and performs good deeds, her reward is also multiplied. This balanced approach shows Allah's perfect justice—greater accountability comes with greater opportunity for reward.",
    "We will grant her double the reward": "They will receive twice the reward of ordinary women for their good deeds. Their unique position, properly utilized, becomes a means of earning extraordinary rewards. This should encourage anyone in a position of influence to use that position for good, knowing that the rewards are magnified.",
    "and We have prepared for her an honourable provision": "Beyond the doubled reward, Allah has prepared for them a noble and generous provision. This refers to their special status in Paradise, their closeness to the Prophet in the hereafter, and the honor they will receive. The provision is described as \"honourable\" (kareem), indicating its exceptional quality and dignity. This was the incentive for choosing the path of Allah and His Messenger over worldly comforts."
  },
  32: {
    "O wives of the Prophet! You are not like any other women": "Allah establishes their unique status. The Prophet's wives are in a category of their own—they have responsibilities and standards that do not apply to other women. They are the Mothers of the Believers, role models for the entire ummah, and the closest humans to the best of creation. This elevated status requires elevated conduct.",
    "if you are mindful ˹of Allah˺": "The special guidelines that follow are connected to their taqwa (God-consciousness). If they truly fear Allah and want to please Him, they will observe these standards. Taqwa is the foundation of all good conduct.",
    "then do not be overly effeminate in speech ˹with men˺": "When speaking to men who are not their mahrams, they should avoid speaking in a soft, alluring, or flirtatious manner. This does not mean being rude or harsh, but rather avoiding tones that could be misinterpreted or that might attract inappropriate attention. The voice can be a tool of attraction, and modesty extends to how one speaks, not just how one dresses.",
    "or those with sickness in their hearts may be tempted": "There are people with corrupt hearts who look for any excuse to entertain improper thoughts or make improper advances. By speaking in a straightforward, businesslike manner, the Prophet's wives would not give such people any opening or encouragement. This guidance protects both the speaker and the listener.",
    "but speak in a moderate tone": "They should speak in a normal, dignified, and straightforward manner—not harsh, but not overly soft or sweet either. The speech should be appropriate to the context and purpose. This principle of moderate, purposeful speech applies to all Muslim women when interacting with non-mahram men."
  },
  33: {
    "Settle in your homes": "The Prophet's wives are advised to make their homes their primary domain. This does not mean they are imprisoned—they could go out for legitimate needs, attend the mosque, visit family, and so on. But their base, their center of activity, should be the home. This provided them protection, dignity, and the ability to focus on their unique responsibilities as the Prophet's wives and teachers of the ummah. From their homes, they taught countless students about Islam.",
    "and do not display yourselves as women did in the days of ˹pre-Islamic˺ ignorance": "Before Islam, women in Arabia would often display their beauty publicly, wearing revealing clothes, walking in ways designed to attract attention, and adorning themselves for public show. The Prophet's wives are forbidden from imitating this behavior. The word \"tabarruj\" means to display beauty and adornments in a way that attracts attention. This pre-Islamic behavior was contrary to the dignity Islam brought to women.",
    "Establish prayer, pay alms-tax, and obey Allah and His Messenger": "These are the core duties: regular prayer, giving charity, and obedience to Allah and His Messenger. The Prophet's wives, despite their special status, were not exempt from any of these obligations. In fact, their consistent practice of these fundamentals was essential to their role as examples for all believing women.",
    "Allah only intends to keep ˹the causes of˺ evil away from you and purify you completely, O members of the ˹Prophet's˺ family": "Allah reveals the purpose behind all these guidelines: to remove impurity and spiritual contamination from the Prophet's household and to purify them completely. These rules are not restrictions but protections. They shield the Prophet's family from sin, scandal, and spiritual harm. The term \"Ahl al-Bayt\" (People of the House) is used here, encompassing the Prophet's wives and, according to many scholars, extending to his close family members. Allah's intention is their purity and honor."
  },
  34: {
    "˹Always˺ remember what is recited in your homes of Allah's revelations and ˹prophetic˺ wisdom": "The Prophet's wives had a unique privilege: the Quran was revealed in their homes, and they witnessed the Prophet's teachings firsthand. They are reminded to treasure, preserve, remember, and share this knowledge. \"Allah's revelations\" refers to the Quran, while \"wisdom\" (hikmah) refers to the Prophet's Sunnah—his sayings, actions, and explanations. The wives became some of the greatest teachers of Islam, with Aisha (may Allah be pleased with her) narrating over 2,000 hadiths. This verse acknowledges their role as preservers and transmitters of Islamic knowledge.",
    "Surely Allah is Most Subtle, All-Aware": "Allah is Lateef (Most Subtle)—He knows the finest details and works in gentle, often imperceptible ways to guide and protect His servants. He is Khabeer (All-Aware)—nothing escapes His knowledge, whether actions, words, or innermost thoughts. These names remind the Prophet's wives (and all believers) that Allah is aware of everything they do and will guide them with His subtle wisdom."
  },
  35: {
    "Surely ˹for˺ Muslim men and women": "This verse beautifully lists categories of righteous people, explicitly mentioning both men and women in each category. This was revealed when Umm Salamah (may Allah be pleased with her) asked the Prophet why women were not mentioned explicitly in the Quran as men were. Allah responded with this comprehensive verse. Being \"Muslim\" means submitting to Allah—accepting His religion and surrendering to His will.",
    "believing men and women": "Believers (mu'mineen) have faith that has entered their hearts. While \"Muslim\" emphasizes outward submission, \"mu'min\" emphasizes inward conviction. Both men and women can attain this level of faith.",
    "devout men and women": "The word \"qanit\" refers to those who are consistently obedient, devoted, and humble before Allah. They maintain their worship and obedience whether in public or private, in ease or difficulty.",
    "truthful men and women": "The truthful (sadiqeen) are honest in their speech, their actions, and their intentions. They do not lie, deceive, or pretend. Their outward behavior matches their inward reality.",
    "patient men and women": "Patient people (sabireen) endure hardships without complaining against Allah, persist in obedience even when it's difficult, and restrain themselves from sins even when tempted.",
    "humble men and women": "The humble (khashi'een) have hearts full of awe and humility before Allah. This humility appears in their prayers, their conduct, and their attitude toward others.",
    "charitable men and women": "Those who give in charity (mutasaddiqeen) spend their wealth for Allah's sake, helping the poor and needy, supporting good causes, and not hoarding their resources.",
    "fasting men and women": "Those who fast (sa'imeen) observe obligatory fasts during Ramadan and often add voluntary fasts throughout the year. Fasting develops self-control and consciousness of Allah.",
    "men and women who guard their chastity": "Those who protect their private parts from unlawful relations, maintaining purity in their intimate lives, avoiding fornication, adultery, and anything that leads to them.",
    "and men and women who remember Allah often": "Those who remember Allah frequently throughout the day—in their words, in their hearts, and in their awareness of His presence. This includes dhikr, prayer, reflection, and gratitude.",
    "for ˹all of˺ them Allah has prepared forgiveness and a great reward": "For all these categories of righteous people—both male and female—Allah has prepared two things: forgiveness for their sins and shortcomings, and a great reward for their good deeds. This verse powerfully affirms that men and women are spiritually equal before Allah. Their gender does not affect their reward; their righteousness does."
  },
  36: {
    "It is not for a believing man or woman—when Allah and His Messenger decree a matter—to have any other choice in that matter": "This verse establishes a fundamental principle of Islam: when Allah and His Messenger have decided something, believers have no option but to obey. This is not tyranny but rather the essence of being a \"Muslim\"—one who submits. Allah's wisdom is perfect, and the Prophet's guidance is divinely inspired. Human preferences and opinions must yield to divine commands. This verse was revealed regarding Zainab bint Jahsh and her initial reluctance (and her brother's) when the Prophet proposed her marriage to Zaid ibn Harithah, his freed slave and adopted son. Despite their hesitation, they submitted when they realized this was Allah's command.",
    "Indeed, whoever disobeys Allah and His Messenger has clearly gone ˹far˺ astray": "Disobedience to Allah and His Messenger is not a minor matter—it is clear misguidance. The word \"mubin\" (clear) emphasizes that such straying is obvious and unmistakable. There is no ambiguity: rejecting divine guidance in favor of personal preference is a departure from the straight path. This warning applies to all believers in all times—whenever a clear command from Allah or His Messenger exists, our personal opinions become irrelevant."
  },
  37: {
    "And ˹remember, O Prophet,˺ when you said to the one for whom Allah has done a favour and you ˹too˺ have done a favour": "This refers to Zaid ibn Harithah. Allah's favor upon him was guiding him to Islam and elevating his status. The Prophet's favor was freeing him from slavery, adopting him, and treating him like a son. Zaid was so honored that he was the only companion mentioned by name in the Quran.",
    "\"Keep your wife and fear Allah\"": "When Zaid came to the Prophet complaining about difficulties in his marriage to Zainab bint Jahsh, the Prophet advised him to stay with his wife and be mindful of Allah. The Prophet genuinely wanted their marriage to work and counseled patience.",
    "while concealing within yourself what Allah was going to reveal": "Allah had already informed the Prophet that Zaid's marriage would end and that he would then marry Zainab. The Prophet knew this but did not want it to happen because he anticipated the social scandal it would cause. He kept encouraging Zaid to stay married, hoping to avoid this difficult situation. This shows the Prophet's humanity—he dreaded the criticism that would come.",
    "And ˹so˺ you were considering the people, whereas Allah was more worthy of your consideration": "Allah gently corrects the Prophet: he was worried about what people would say, but Allah's command should have been his primary concern. This is not a harsh rebuke but a reminder that divine commands take precedence over social concerns. If Allah decrees something, the opinions of people become secondary. This correction, preserved in the Quran, shows the book's authenticity—the Prophet would not have included such a verse if he were its author.",
    "So when Zaid totally lost interest in ˹keeping˺ his wife, We gave her to you in marriage": "After all efforts to save the marriage failed and Zaid divorced Zainab, Allah Himself arranged the marriage between the Prophet and Zainab. The verse says \"We gave her to you in marriage\"—Allah was the one who joined them. There was no ceremony in the traditional sense; the divine command itself was the marriage contract.",
    "so that there would be no blame on the believers for marrying the ex-wives of their adopted sons after their divorce": "This is the wisdom behind this entire situation. In pre-Islamic Arabia, an adopted son was considered exactly like a biological son, so marrying his ex-wife would be like marrying one's daughter-in-law—a grave taboo. By commanding the Prophet to marry Zainab (his adopted son's ex-wife), Allah practically demonstrated that adoption does not create the same prohibitions as biological parentage. If even the Prophet did this, ordinary Muslims certainly could. The Prophet personally endured criticism to establish this important legal principle for the entire ummah.",
    "And Allah's command is totally binding": "What Allah decrees will happen. His commands are executed without fail. The Prophet's reluctance could not prevent what Allah had decreed, and the criticism of people could not change Allah's plan. This phrase reassures believers that Allah's will always prevails."
  },
  38: {
    "There is no blame on the Prophet for doing what Allah has ordained for him": "Allah explicitly clears the Prophet of any wrongdoing. What he did was not his personal desire but Allah's command. No one should criticize the Prophet for following divine orders. This verse defends the Prophet against the accusations that were circulating among the hypocrites.",
    "That has been the way of Allah with those ˹prophets˺ who had gone before": "Previous prophets also followed Allah's commands regarding marriage and other matters, even when those commands seemed unusual to their societies. David, Solomon, and other prophets had multiple marriages. The prophets are not judged by ordinary standards because they receive special commands from Allah.",
    "And Allah's command has been firmly decreed": "Allah's decrees are precise and predetermined. Everything happens according to His perfect plan and timing. The events surrounding Zaid and Zainab were not random but were part of Allah's carefully measured decree to establish important legal principles."
  },
  39: {
    "˹That is His way with˺ those ˹prophets˺ who deliver the messages of Allah": "This describes the prophets: they faithfully convey whatever Allah reveals to them, regardless of how difficult or controversial the message may be. They do not hide or alter anything to avoid criticism.",
    "and consider Him, and none but Allah": "The prophets fear only Allah. They are not swayed by fear of people, social pressure, or personal consequences. Their sole concern is pleasing Allah and fulfilling their mission. This is the standard for all believers: to fear Allah above all else.",
    "And sufficient is Allah as a ˹vigilant˺ Reckoner": "Allah is enough to keep account of everything. He knows who obeys and who disobeys, who is sincere and who is hypocritical. The prophets trust Him to vindicate them, and the critics will face His accounting. Believers should take comfort that Allah sees all and will judge fairly."
  },
  40: {
    "Muḥammad is not the father of any of your men": "This clarifies that despite having adopted Zaid, the Prophet is not truly the father of any adult man in the community. His biological sons all died in childhood. Therefore, the prohibitions that apply to biological fathers do not apply to him regarding Zaid's ex-wife. This also explains why he has no male heir to continue his lineage—his legacy is his message, not a dynasty.",
    "but is the Messenger of Allah and the seal of the prophets": "The Prophet's primary identity is not as a father but as Allah's Messenger. More significantly, he is the \"seal\" (khatam) of the prophets—the final one, after whom there will be no more prophets. This is a fundamental Islamic belief. The prophetic mission is complete with Muhammad (peace be upon him), and anyone claiming prophethood after him is false.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of all things": "Allah knows everything—why He chose Muhammad as the final prophet, why events unfolded as they did, and what wisdom lies behind every decree. Human beings may not understand everything, but Allah's perfect knowledge ensures that everything is as it should be."
  },
  41: {
    "O believers! Always remember Allah often": "Allah commands the believers to engage in frequent remembrance of Him. This includes verbal dhikr (saying SubhanAllah, Alhamdulillah, Allahu Akbar, etc.), mental awareness of Allah's presence, and living in a way that reflects consciousness of Him. The word \"katheeran\" (much/often) indicates this should not be occasional but constant. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"The example of one who remembers his Lord and one who does not is like the living and the dead\" (Bukhari). Dhikr keeps the heart alive and connected to Allah."
  },
  42: {
    "and glorify Him morning and evening": "Believers should especially remember Allah at the beginning and end of the day. The morning and evening adhkar (remembrances) taught by the Prophet provide protection, blessings, and spiritual nourishment. Starting and ending the day with Allah's remembrance frames the entire day within divine consciousness. These times—when the world transitions between light and darkness—are particularly significant for connecting with the Creator."
  },
  43: {
    "He is the One Who showers His blessings upon you": "When Allah \"sends salah\" upon someone, it means He mentions them with praise among the angels. This is an incredible honor—the Creator of the universe blessing His servants. Some scholars say it means Allah shows mercy to them. Either way, it indicates Allah's special care and attention toward the believers.",
    "and His angels pray for you": "The angels also supplicate for the believers, asking Allah to forgive them, guide them, and have mercy on them. Imagine countless angels constantly praying for your wellbeing—this is what believers receive. The Prophet said: \"The angels send blessings upon any one of you so long as he remains in his prayer place\" (Bukhari). Believers are surrounded by angelic support.",
    "so that He may bring you out of darkness and into light": "The purpose of Allah's blessings and the angels' prayers is to guide believers from darkness to light—from ignorance to knowledge, from sin to righteousness, from misguidance to guidance, from despair to hope. Darkness here represents all forms of spiritual confusion and harm, while light represents faith, clarity, and salvation.",
    "For He is ever Merciful to the believers": "Allah is especially merciful to those who believe. His mercy for believers is constant and unwavering. This does not mean disbelievers receive no mercy in this world, but the special, saving mercy is reserved for believers. This should fill every believer with hope and gratitude."
  },
  44: {
    "Their greeting on the Day they meet Him will be, \"Peace!\"": "When believers meet Allah on the Day of Judgment, they will be greeted with \"Salam\" (Peace). This greeting indicates safety from punishment, acceptance into Allah's mercy, and ultimate success. After all the fears of that Day, believers will hear \"Peace\"—what greater relief could there be? Some scholars say this greeting comes from Allah Himself, while others say it comes from the angels on His behalf.",
    "And He has prepared for them an honourable reward": "Paradise and its delights await the believers—a reward described as \"kareem\" (honourable/generous). This word indicates not just quantity but quality—a reward befitting the dignity and honor that Allah bestows upon His faithful servants. Everything in Paradise will be noble, beautiful, and beyond human imagination."
  },
  45: {
    "O Prophet! We have sent you as a witness": "The Prophet serves as a witness—a witness over his ummah on the Day of Judgment, testifying about whether they received and followed the message. He also witnessed the truth firsthand through revelation. His life and teachings serve as testimony to the truth of Islam.",
    "and a deliverer of good news": "The Prophet brings glad tidings to believers—news of Allah's mercy, forgiveness, and the rewards of Paradise. His message is not only warnings; it includes beautiful promises for those who believe and do good. This gives hope and motivation to strive for Allah's pleasure.",
    "and a warner": "He also warns people of the consequences of disbelief and sin—the punishment of this world and the hereafter. A complete messenger brings both hope and fear, encouraging people toward good and cautioning them against evil. The Prophet fulfilled both roles perfectly."
  },
  46: {
    "and a caller to ˹the Way of˺ Allah by His command": "The Prophet invites people to Allah—to His worship, His obedience, and His path. He does this not on his own initiative but \"by His command\"—he only calls to what Allah authorizes. This protects the message from human additions or alterations.",
    "and a beacon of light": "The Prophet is described as a \"luminous lamp\" (siraj muneer)—he illuminates the darkness of ignorance, misguidance, and sin. Just as a lamp guides travelers at night, the Prophet's guidance leads humanity through the darkness of this world toward the light of truth and salvation. His teachings continue to light the way for all who follow him."
  },
  47: {
    "Give good news to the believers that they will have a great bounty from Allah": "The Prophet is commanded to specifically announce to the believers that a great favor awaits them from Allah. This \"fadl\" (bounty/favor) includes forgiveness, Paradise, Allah's pleasure, and blessings beyond imagination. Believers should be encouraged by this promise and motivated to remain steadfast."
  },
  48: {
    "Do not yield to the disbelievers and the hypocrites": "This repeats the command from the beginning of the surah, creating a thematic bracket. The Prophet must never compromise the truth to please those who reject it or pretend to accept it while harboring disbelief.",
    "Overlook their annoyances": "Rather than being consumed by their insults, plots, and harassment, the Prophet should rise above it. He should not retaliate for personal grievances or become distracted by their provocations. His focus should remain on his mission.",
    "and put your trust in Allah": "Trust in Allah is the solution to dealing with opposition. When enemies attack, rely on Allah. When hypocrites plot, rely on Allah. This trust frees the heart from anxiety and allows the Prophet (and all believers) to continue their work with confidence.",
    "For Allah is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs": "The verse ends exactly as the earlier verse (33:3) did—affirming that Allah is enough to manage all affairs. With Allah as their Trustee, believers need not fear any enemy or plot. He is sufficient, and those who trust Him are never disappointed."
  },
  49: {
    "O believers! If you marry believing women and then divorce them before you touch them": "This verse addresses a specific situation: when a man marries a woman but divorces her before the marriage is consummated (before intimacy occurs). The marriage contract was valid, but the physical relationship never began.",
    "they will have no waiting period for you to count": "In such cases, the divorced woman does not need to observe the standard waiting period (iddah). Normally, a divorced woman waits three menstrual cycles before remarrying to ensure she is not pregnant from the previous marriage. But if there was no intimacy, there is no possibility of pregnancy, so no waiting period is required. She is free to remarry immediately.",
    "so give them a ˹suitable˺ compensation": "Even though the marriage was not consummated, the woman should still receive compensation (mut'ah). This is a gift to help her transition and acknowledge that she entered into a marriage agreement in good faith. Islam ensures women are treated with dignity even when marriages do not work out.",
    "and let them go graciously": "The divorce should be conducted kindly and respectfully. There should be no harsh words, public humiliation, or bitterness. The relationship ends, but the treatment remains honorable. This phrase (used multiple times in these verses) emphasizes Islam's insistence on dignity in all circumstances."
  },
  50: {
    "O Prophet! We have made lawful for you your wives to whom you have paid their ˹full˺ dowries": "Allah addresses the Prophet regarding who is lawful for him in marriage. First mentioned are his current wives whose dowries (mahr) he has paid. The dowry is a woman's right in Islam, and the Prophet fulfilled this right for all his wives.",
    "as well as those ˹bondwomen˺ in your possession, whom Allah has granted you": "Also lawful were bondwomen who came into his possession through legitimate means. This was a reality of that time, and Islam regulated such relationships while encouraging and facilitating emancipation.",
    "And ˹you are allowed to marry˺ the daughters of your paternal uncles and aunts, and the daughters of your maternal uncles and aunts, who have emigrated like you": "The Prophet could marry from among his cousins—daughters of his father's brothers and sisters, and his mother's brothers and sisters—provided they had emigrated (made hijrah). The condition of emigration was specific to that time, distinguishing those who had sacrificed for Islam from those who had not yet made that commitment.",
    "Also ˹allowed for marriage is˺ a believing woman who offers herself to the Prophet ˹without dowry˺ if he is interested in marrying her": "A unique ruling allowed a believing woman to offer herself in marriage to the Prophet without requiring a dowry, if the Prophet wished to accept. This did not obligate the Prophet to marry such women—it only permitted it if he chose.",
    "˹this is˺ exclusively for you, not for the rest of the believers": "This specific allowance (marrying without dowry) was only for the Prophet, not for ordinary Muslims. Regular Muslim men must pay dowry when they marry. Allah makes clear which rulings are specific to the Prophet and which apply to everyone.",
    "We know well what ˹rulings˺ We have ordained for the believers in relation to their wives and those ˹bondwomen˺ in their possession": "Allah affirms His knowledge of all the marriage rules He has established for the general Muslim community. The Prophet has some different rulings, but Allah is fully aware of what applies to whom.",
    "As such, there would be no blame on you": "These detailed clarifications remove any confusion or blame. The Prophet is not doing anything wrong by following rules that are specifically for him. Allah has made everything clear.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "The verse ends with these comforting names, indicating Allah's understanding of human needs and His mercy in providing clear guidance. Even if mistakes occur, Allah's forgiveness is available for those who repent."
  },
  51: {
    "It is up to you ˹O Prophet˺ to delay or receive whoever you please of your wives": "Allah grants the Prophet flexibility in managing his time with his wives. He could choose to spend time with whomever he wished and delay visiting others. This was a relief given the practical challenges of managing a household with multiple wives, each with different needs and circumstances. The Prophet had unique responsibilities that no other husband had—leading a nation, receiving revelation, teaching, judging disputes, and more.",
    "There is no blame on you if you call back any of those you have set aside": "If the Prophet had previously set aside a particular wife's turn (perhaps due to his schedule or other circumstances), he was free to call her back without any sin. This flexibility prevented rigid rules from causing unnecessary hardship for him or his wives.",
    "That is more likely that they will be content, not grieved, and satisfied with what you offer them all": "Allah explains the wisdom: this arrangement was designed to bring contentment to all the wives. When they understood that this flexibility came from Allah Himself, they would accept the Prophet's decisions without jealousy or grief. They knew Allah was orchestrating matters for everyone's wellbeing. The key to their contentment was knowing that Allah was aware of their situation and had made these allowances.",
    "Allah ˹fully˺ knows what is in your hearts": "Allah knows the inner feelings of the Prophet and his wives—the love, the potential jealousy, the desire for attention, and every other emotion. Nothing is hidden from Him. This awareness provides comfort: Allah understands everyone's feelings and has made rulings accordingly.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, Most Forbearing": "Allah combines knowledge with forbearance. He knows human weaknesses and is patient with them. He does not immediately punish for jealous thoughts or momentary frustrations. His forbearance allows people time to adjust and improve."
  },
  52: {
    "It is not lawful for you ˹O Prophet˺ to marry more women after this": "After Allah granted the Prophet his existing wives, He prohibited him from marrying any additional women. This limitation was placed on the Prophet specifically. It honored his current wives by ensuring they would not be joined by others, and it refuted any accusation that the Prophet married out of desire for women—if that were true, why would he accept this restriction?",
    "nor can you replace any of your present wives with another, even if her beauty may attract you": "The Prophet could not divorce any of his current wives to marry someone else, even if another woman's beauty attracted him. This was further protection for his wives—they had chosen him and the hereafter (as mentioned earlier in the surah), and now Allah guaranteed their position. This also showed that the Prophet's marriages were not about physical attraction but about divine wisdom and purposes.",
    "except those ˹bondwomen˺ in your possession": "The exception was bondwomen, which was regulated differently than marriage in that society. This exception did not contradict the protection offered to his wives.",
    "And Allah is ever Watchful over all things": "Allah observes everything—every glance, every thought, every action. This reminder keeps both the Prophet and the believers conscious of Allah's constant awareness. Nothing escapes His knowledge."
  },
  53: {
    "O believers! Do not enter the homes of the Prophet without permission": "Basic etiquette is established: no one should enter the Prophet's home without being invited. The Prophet's home was his private space, and like anyone else, he deserved privacy and respect. This verse was revealed after some companions would enter freely, sometimes at inconvenient times.",
    "˹and if invited˺ for a meal, do not ˹come too early and˺ linger until the meal is ready": "If invited for a meal, guests should not arrive too early and sit around waiting for the food to be prepared. This would burden the host and create awkwardness. Coming at the appropriate time shows consideration for the host's schedule and effort.",
    "But if you are invited, then enter ˹on time˺": "When invited, come at the designated time—not too early, not too late. This teaches proper social etiquette that applies to visiting anyone, not just the Prophet.",
    "Once you have eaten, then go on your way, and do not stay for casual talk": "After the meal, guests should leave and not linger for lengthy conversations. Extended stays burden the host, who may have other responsibilities or need rest. This was especially important for the Prophet, whose time was extremely valuable for the entire ummah.",
    "Such behaviour is truly annoying to the Prophet, yet he is too shy to ask you to leave": "Allah reveals something the Prophet himself would never say: lingering guests annoyed him. His noble character prevented him from asking people to leave, so Allah intervened to protect him. This shows the Prophet's exceptional shyness and good manners, even when he was inconvenienced.",
    "But Allah is never shy of the truth": "While the Prophet was too polite to speak up, Allah has no such hesitation. When something needs to be said for people's benefit, Allah says it directly. Truth must be spoken even when it's uncomfortable.",
    "And when you ˹believers˺ ask his wives for something, ask them from behind a barrier": "This is a key verse for hijab. When men needed to speak to the Prophet's wives—to ask questions about religion or request something—they should do so from behind a screen or curtain, not face-to-face. This was the beginning of the hijab legislation.",
    "This is purer for your hearts and theirs": "The wisdom is explained: physical barriers protect the hearts of both men and women. Even righteous people can be affected by attraction, so preventive measures maintain purity. This is not about distrust but about protection and prevention.",
    "And it is not right for you to annoy the Messenger of Allah": "Causing any annoyance to the Prophet is forbidden. This includes violating his privacy, burdening his household, or any behavior that would disturb him.",
    "nor ever marry his wives after him": "The Prophet's wives are permanently forbidden from marrying anyone else, even after the Prophet's death. This is because they are the Mothers of the Believers—marrying them would be like marrying one's own mother. It also preserved their dignity and the Prophet's honor.",
    "This would certainly be a major offence in the sight of Allah": "Marrying the Prophet's widows would be a tremendous sin. Allah does not use such strong language lightly. This shows the seriousness of respecting the Prophet's household and his unique position."
  },
  54: {
    "Whether you reveal something or conceal it, surely Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of all things": "This verse serves as a reminder after the previous guidelines. Whether people openly discuss inappropriate intentions regarding the Prophet's wives or hide such thoughts in their hearts, Allah knows everything. This warning ensures people purify not just their actions but also their thoughts and intentions. Nothing is hidden from Allah."
  },
  55: {
    "There is no blame on the Prophet's wives ˹if they appear unveiled˺ before their fathers": "While the previous verse established hijab before non-mahram men, this verse clarifies who is exempt. The Prophet's wives do not need to observe hijab before their fathers—their own fathers whom they grew up with.",
    "their sons, their brothers, their brothers' sons, their sisters' sons": "Also exempt are their sons, brothers, nephews from both brothers' and sisters' sides. These are all mahram relatives—men who are permanently forbidden from marrying them and with whom there is a natural family bond.",
    "their fellow ˹Muslim˺ women, and those ˹bondspeople˺ in their possession": "Other Muslim women and any bondspeople they possessed were also included in those before whom hijab was not required. Between women, there is no requirement for hijab (though modesty is still expected).",
    "And be mindful of Allah ˹O wives of the Prophet!˺": "A reminder to maintain taqwa (consciousness of Allah) in all situations. Even when relaxed rules apply with certain people, overall God-consciousness should guide behavior.",
    "Surely Allah is a Witness over all things": "Allah witnesses everything—how the Prophet's wives conduct themselves in private and public, how they interact with mahrams and non-mahrams. His witness serves as both a reminder and a comfort."
  },
  56: {
    "Indeed, Allah showers His blessings upon the Prophet, and His angels pray for him": "This is one of the most honored verses about the Prophet's status. Allah Himself sends salah (blessings, praise, mercy) upon the Prophet, and the angels continuously pray for him. When Allah \"sends salah,\" scholars say it means He praises the Prophet among the highest assembly of angels. When angels send salah, they are making dua for him. The Prophet is constantly receiving blessings from the highest sources.",
    "O believers! Invoke Allah's blessings upon him, and salute him with worthy greetings of peace": "After mentioning what Allah and the angels do, believers are commanded to do the same. We should send salah (blessings) upon the Prophet and salam (peace) upon him. This is done by saying \"Sallallahu alayhi wa sallam\" (May Allah send blessings and peace upon him). The Prophet said: \"Whoever sends blessings upon me once, Allah will send blessings upon him ten times\" (Muslim). This is both an honor for the Prophet and a means of reward for the believers. It is especially emphasized on Fridays and whenever the Prophet's name is mentioned."
  },
  57: {
    "Surely those who offend Allah and His Messenger": "Those who cause offense to Allah—through disbelief, ascribing partners to Him, denying His attributes, or disobeying His commands—and those who harm His Messenger through mockery, insults, or rejection, have committed grave sins. Offending Allah includes all forms of shirk and kufr. Offending the Prophet includes any disrespect or harm directed toward him or his message.",
    "are condemned by Allah in this world and the Hereafter": "Such people are cursed (la'nah) by Allah—expelled from His mercy. This curse applies both in this life (where they are deprived of guidance and blessing) and in the hereafter (where they face eternal consequences). Being cursed by Allah is the worst possible state.",
    "And He has prepared for them a humiliating punishment": "Their punishment is described as \"muheen\" (humiliating). It is not just painful but degrading. Those who tried to humiliate Allah's religion and His Messenger will themselves be humiliated. The punishment fits the crime."
  },
  58: {
    "As for those who abuse believing men and women unjustifiably": "This verse protects the honor of all believers. Those who harm, insult, slander, or abuse believing men and women without just cause (meaning they did not commit any wrong that would warrant criticism) are committing a serious sin. This includes spreading rumors, false accusations, mockery, and all forms of unjust harm.",
    "they will definitely bear the guilt of slander and blatant sin": "Such people carry two burdens: \"buhtan\" (slander/false accusation) and \"ithm mubeen\" (clear sin). Slander is lying about someone, and the sin is clear and obvious—there is no ambiguity about its wrongness. The Prophet said: \"A Muslim is one from whose tongue and hand other Muslims are safe\" (Bukhari). Harming believers is a betrayal of the Muslim brotherhood."
  },
  59: {
    "O Prophet! Ask your wives, daughters, and believing women to draw their cloaks over their bodies": "This verse extends the hijab command beyond the Prophet's wives to all believing women. The \"jilbab\" (cloak/outer garment) should be drawn over their bodies when they go out. This provides coverage and modesty in public settings. The command is clear and includes three categories: the Prophet's wives, his daughters, and all believing women—showing this is a universal Islamic ruling, not specific to one group.",
    "In this way it is more likely that they will be recognized ˹as virtuous˺ and not be harassed": "The wisdom behind hijab is explained: it serves as a means of identification and protection. When a woman is modestly dressed, she is recognized as a respectable, God-conscious Muslim woman. This recognition deters ill-intentioned people from harassing her. In the context of Medina at that time, there were people who would harass women, and they often targeted those who appeared less modest. The hijab served as protection.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "This conclusion reminds believers that Allah is forgiving for past shortcomings (before this command was revealed or before one began practicing it) and merciful in providing guidance that protects. It also indicates that if someone sincerely struggles with this command, Allah's mercy is available for those who are trying."
  },
  60: {
    "If the hypocrites, and those with sickness in their hearts, and rumour-mongers in Medina do not desist": "Three groups are warned: (1) hypocrites—those who pretend to be Muslim while concealing disbelief, (2) those with sick hearts—people with weak faith, lustful intentions, or corrupt thoughts, and (3) rumor-mongers—those who spread frightening news, false information, and propaganda to destabilize the community. These groups were actively harming the Muslim society in Medina.",
    "We will certainly incite you ˹O Prophet˺ against them": "Allah warns that He will command the Prophet to take action against them if they do not stop. This \"incitement\" means Allah will reveal commands and grant permission for the Prophet to confront these troublemakers directly.",
    "and then they will not be your neighbours there any longer": "The consequence of continued mischief would be expulsion from Medina. They would no longer be allowed to live alongside the Muslim community. This was a serious threat in that society, where tribal belonging and place of residence were everything."
  },
  61: {
    "˹They deserve to be˺ condemned": "They are cursed—expelled from Allah's mercy. Their activities of hypocrisy, spreading corruption, and rumor-mongering have earned them divine condemnation.",
    "˹If they were to persist,˺ they would get themselves seized and killed relentlessly wherever they are found": "If they continued their harmful activities, the severe punishment would be that wherever they were found, they would be captured and executed. This was the consequence for those who actively worked to destroy the Muslim community from within during a time of war and existential threat. The ruling here is specific to active treachery and sedition during wartime, not a general license."
  },
  62: {
    "That was Allah's way with those ˹hypocrites˺ who have gone before": "This punishment for hypocrites and traitors is not new—it was how Allah dealt with similar people in previous communities. Those who betrayed their prophets and communities from within faced similar consequences throughout history.",
    "And you will find no change in Allah's way": "Allah's patterns and ways (sunan) do not change. How He deals with righteousness, sin, hypocrisy, and treachery remains consistent throughout time. This is a warning for all future generations: the same behaviors will produce the same consequences."
  },
  63: {
    "People ask you ˹O Prophet˺ about the Hour": "People frequently asked the Prophet about the Day of Judgment—when it would occur. This curiosity is natural, but Allah had not revealed this information to anyone, including the Prophet. In the famous hadith of Jibreel, when asked about the Hour, the Prophet replied: \"The one being asked knows no more than the one asking\" (Muslim).",
    "Say, \"That knowledge is only with Allah\"": "The Prophet is instructed to clearly state that only Allah knows when the Hour will come. No angel, prophet, or any other creation has this knowledge. It is part of the unseen that Allah has kept exclusively to Himself. This teaches humility and prevents false predictions.",
    "\"You never know, perhaps the Hour is near\"": "While the exact time is unknown, the Hour could be close. This uncertainty should keep people in a state of readiness. Every generation should live as if the Hour could come in their lifetime. The Prophet said: \"The Hour and I were sent like these two,\" holding up his index and middle fingers together (Bukhari), indicating their closeness."
  },
  64: {
    "Surely Allah condemns the disbelievers": "Those who reject faith are cursed by Allah—removed from His mercy. This is the consequence of deliberately rejecting the truth after it has been made clear.",
    "and has prepared for them a blazing Fire": "Hell (Sa'eer—a blazing, fierce fire) has already been prepared and is waiting for them. The use of past tense (\"has prepared\") emphasizes certainty—it already exists and is ready."
  },
  65: {
    "to stay there for ever and ever": "Their punishment is eternal—they will remain in Hellfire forever. There is no end, no release, no escape. The word \"abadan\" (forever) removes any hope of eventual exit.",
    "never will they find any protector or helper": "In Hellfire, they will have no ally to support them and no helper to rescue them. All the false gods they worshipped, all the powerful people they followed, all the wealth they accumulated—none of it will benefit them. They will be utterly alone in their punishment."
  },
  66: {
    "On the Day their faces are ˹constantly˺ flipped in the Fire": "The disbelievers' faces—the most honored part of the body, the part people are most protective of—will be turned over and over in the flames. This is a humiliating and agonizing punishment, targeting specifically what they were proudest of.",
    "they will cry, \"Oh! If only we had obeyed Allah and obeyed the Messenger!\"": "In their agony, they will express regret. If only they had listened! If only they had followed the truth! But this regret comes too late. The time for action was in worldly life, and they wasted it. Now they can only wish for what cannot be changed."
  },
  67: {
    "And they will say, \"Our Lord! We obeyed our leaders and elite, but they led us astray from the ˹Right˺ Way\"": "They will try to shift blame to their leaders—the influential people, the wealthy, the intellectuals, the religious authorities who misguided them. They followed these elites instead of following the prophets and the truth. But this excuse will not help them. Each person is responsible for their own choices. Following corrupt leaders does not absolve followers of responsibility, especially when the truth was available."
  },
  68: {
    "\"Our Lord! Give them double ˹our˺ punishment, and condemn them tremendously\"": "In their misery, the followers will pray against their former leaders, asking Allah to double their punishment and curse them severely. Those who seemed so important in the world, whose approval people sought, will now be the object of curses from their own followers. This shows how worldly relationships based on falsehood will turn to enmity on Judgment Day."
  },
  69: {
    "O believers! Do not be like those who slandered Moses": "Believers are warned not to follow the example of those who harmed Prophet Musa (Moses) through their words and actions. The Children of Israel frequently complained against Musa, accused him, and caused him distress. Some scholars mention the specific incident where they accused him of having a physical defect, and Allah cleared him miraculously. Others mention various other instances of their harmful speech against him.",
    "but Allah cleared him of what they said": "Whatever false accusations or hurtful things they said about Musa, Allah vindicated him and proved his innocence. The truth always prevails eventually, and those who slander prophets or righteous people will be exposed.",
    "And he was honourable in the sight of Allah": "Musa held a position of honor and high esteem with Allah. The opinions and slanders of people did not diminish his rank with his Lord. This is comforting for anyone who faces false accusations while doing Allah's work—what matters is one's standing with Allah, not with people."
  },
  70: {
    "O believers! Be mindful of Allah": "Believers are again called to taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads to obedience and avoidance of sin. This is the foundation of all righteousness.",
    "and say what is right": "Speech should be \"sadeed\"—straight, correct, appropriate, and true. This includes being truthful, avoiding harmful speech, speaking with purpose, and choosing words that are beneficial. The Prophet said: \"Whoever believes in Allah and the Last Day should speak good or remain silent\" (Bukhari). Right speech is a manifestation of taqwa."
  },
  71: {
    "He will bless your deeds for you": "If believers maintain taqwa and speak correctly, Allah will rectify and improve their deeds. He will make their actions beneficial, accepted, and fruitful. Good speech leads to good actions, and Allah blesses the efforts of the sincere.",
    "and forgive your sins": "Along with improving deeds, Allah will forgive past sins. Taqwa and righteous speech become means of earning forgiveness. This dual benefit—improved future actions and forgiven past sins—is a tremendous reward.",
    "And whoever obeys Allah and His Messenger, has truly achieved a great triumph": "The ultimate success is defined: obedience to Allah and His Messenger. Not wealth, not fame, not worldly achievements—but obedience. This obedience leads to \"fawz azeem\"—the greatest triumph: Paradise, Allah's pleasure, and eternal success."
  },
  72: {
    "Indeed, We offered the trust to the heavens and the earth and the mountains": "Allah presented a great \"amanah\" (trust/responsibility) to the mightiest of creations: the vast heavens, the solid earth, and the towering mountains. Scholars have explained this \"trust\" in various ways: some say it refers to the duties of Islam and its commands; others say it is the capacity for free will and moral choice; others say it encompasses all responsibilities Allah places on His servants—prayers, fasting, honesty, fulfilling obligations, etc.",
    "but they ˹all˺ declined to bear it, being fearful of it": "These massive creations—heavens, earth, and mountains—refused to carry this trust. They were afraid of the consequences of failing to fulfill it. They recognized the weight of the responsibility and, in their wisdom and submission to Allah, declined. They continue to fulfill their roles without the burden of moral accountability.",
    "But humanity assumed it": "Human beings, however, took on this responsibility. We accepted the trust that even the mountains feared. This acceptance is what makes human beings unique—we have moral agency, free will, and accountability that other creations do not have.",
    "˹for˺ they are truly wrongful ˹to themselves˺ and ignorant ˹of the consequences˺": "Humanity is described as \"dhaaloom\" (very wrongful) and \"jahool\" (very ignorant). This is not merely an insult but a recognition of human nature: we often wrong ourselves through sin and fail to appreciate the gravity of our responsibilities. We underestimate consequences and overestimate our abilities. Yet within this weakness lies potential—those who overcome their wrongfulness and ignorance through faith and obedience achieve ranks that even angels do not reach."
  },
  73: {
    "so that Allah will punish hypocrite men and women and polytheistic men and women": "The purpose of this test—this trust and accountability—is to distinguish people. Those who betray the trust through hypocrisy (pretending faith while hiding disbelief) or shirk (associating partners with Allah) will be punished. They were given the opportunity, they had the capacity, and they chose wrong.",
    "and Allah will turn in mercy to believing men and women": "On the other hand, those who honor the trust through sincere faith will receive Allah's mercy and forgiveness. Their struggle to fulfill their responsibilities, despite their human weaknesses, will be rewarded with Allah's tawbah (turning to them in acceptance and mercy).",
    "For Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "The surah concludes with these two beautiful names, emphasizing hope. Despite human weakness, despite the heavy burden of the trust, despite past failures—Allah's forgiveness and mercy are available. Those who turn to Him, strive to fulfill their responsibilities, and seek His pardon will find Him ready to forgive and shower them with mercy. This is the perfect conclusion to a surah that has discussed weighty matters of war, family law, social conduct, and cosmic responsibility."
  }
};